Let's go, let's go! Now, now, now!

1512
01:27:02,366 --> 01:27:03,407
Daniel?

1513
01:27:03,843 --> 01:27:06,845
You'd be right
if you weren't so wrong.

1514
01:27:07,263 --> 01:27:08,972
While you're watching the magician,

1515
01:27:09,640 --> 01:27:12,225
that lovely innocent is actually
pulling the strings.

1516
01:27:12,310 --> 01:27:15,395
Don't you find it peculiar that Interpol
would send you

1517
01:27:15,479 --> 01:27:18,982
a first timer off the desk to be your assistant?

1518
01:27:19,483 --> 01:27:21,651
Why did she request to be put on the case?

1519
01:27:21,986 --> 01:27:23,945
She was assigned to the case.

1520
01:27:24,947 --> 01:27:26,323
Luck of the draw.

1521
01:27:26,782 --> 01:27:29,826
Like choosing a random card in the deck.

1522
01:27:30,036 --> 01:27:33,580
I find it odd, your sudden act of generosity.

1523
01:27:33,664 --> 01:27:34,831
What's in it for you?

1524
01:27:34,999 --> 01:27:36,833
Just trying to even the game.

1525
01:27:37,126 --> 01:27:40,962
I feel like I'm playing with somebody
wearing ankle weights and flippers.

1526
01:27:42,173 --> 01:27:45,967
Keep up, Agent Rhodes. Keep up.

1527
01:27:49,805 --> 01:27:50,847
Hey.

1528
01:27:51,182 --> 01:27:52,390
We got a problem.

1529
01:27:53,559 --> 01:27:54,643
Here's the safe.

1530
01:27:54,727 --> 01:27:57,520
No, no, no. Hey. What's he doing here?

1531
01:27:57,688 --> 01:27:59,147
Giving us our first solid lead.

1532
01:27:59,231 --> 01:28:02,317
We've been investigating a private security
contractor called Elkhorn

1533
01:28:02,401 --> 01:28:04,069
- for the last five years.
- And?

1534
01:28:04,153 --> 01:28:06,279
They've been hiding close
to a half billion dollars...

1535
01:28:06,364 --> 01:28:08,865
I didn't ask you. I asked him.

1536
01:28:09,241 --> 01:28:11,451
The money's in a vault inside
a warehouse in Queens.

1537
01:28:11,535 --> 01:28:14,037
We think this vault
is your magicians' final target.

1538
01:28:14,413 --> 01:28:16,122
The magician
who died on the bridge...

1539
01:28:16,207 --> 01:28:19,834
You pulled our classified Elkhorn file
right from his crispy little hand.

1540
01:28:20,127 --> 01:28:22,462
And despite their bullshit
Robin Hood razzle-dazzle,

1541
01:28:22,546 --> 01:28:24,297
your magicians are nothing
more than common thieves.

1542
01:28:24,382 --> 01:28:25,548
How did they get the file?

1543
01:28:27,009 --> 01:28:30,011
This is the part you're gonna find
particularly interesting, Agent Rhodes.

1544
01:28:30,221 --> 01:28:34,933
They patched to my server after they accessed
your mobile command center in New Orleans

1545
01:28:35,017 --> 01:28:36,601
with codes they got from your phone.

1546
01:28:38,729 --> 01:28:40,563
You ordered us all out to chase after them.

1547
01:28:41,023 --> 01:28:43,483
The level of incompetence
displayed on this case,

1548
01:28:43,567 --> 01:28:45,568
that's a magic trick in and of itself.

1549
01:28:46,237 --> 01:28:48,530
Abracadabra. I'm taking over.

1550
01:28:49,949 --> 01:28:51,866
Boss, he's taking over?

1551
01:28:52,410 --> 01:28:53,910
Let's go, gentlemen.

1552
01:28:55,746 --> 01:28:56,746
Hey.

1553
01:28:56,872 --> 01:28:58,748
Hey. I want to have a word with you.

1554
01:28:58,833 --> 01:28:59,958
Don't ever talk to me like that again.

1555
01:29:00,042 --> 01:29:02,419
- Why the hell did you take this case?
- What?

1556
01:29:02,503 --> 01:29:04,587
People say I'm hard to read.
That's an American expression.

1557
01:29:04,672 --> 01:29:05,922
Do you understand it?

1558
01:29:06,048 --> 01:29:07,090
Yes.

1559
01:29:07,216 --> 01:29:09,217
Good, then let me make myself
perfectly clear to you.

1560
01:29:09,427 --> 01:29:13,221
If I find out that you are anything other than
who you say you are, I swear...

1561
01:29:13,347 --> 01:29:15,056
And we French also have an expression.

1562
01:29:16,934 --> 01:29:18,518
Faith can move mountains.

1563
01:29:18,728 --> 01:29:22,355
If we hope to capture The Horsemen,
then you need to have a little faith in me.

1564
01:29:22,565 --> 01:29:24,566
Because I've done nothing
to deserve otherwise.

1565
01:29:24,734 --> 01:29:27,360
I just got my ass handed to me.

1566
01:29:27,445 --> 01:29:28,987
I am losing this case.

1567
01:29:29,071 --> 01:29:32,407
So faith is a luxury
I don't have any time for right now.

1568
01:29:38,622 --> 01:29:40,832
More than anything in his life,

1569
01:29:40,916 --> 01:29:46,337
Jack wanted to be
the most famous magician who ever lived.

1570
01:29:46,422 --> 01:29:47,797
And I can't say he achieved it,

1571
01:29:47,882 --> 01:29:51,801
but I do hope wherever he is,
it is full of magic.

1572
01:29:53,596 --> 01:29:55,930
But the point is... Sorry.

1573
01:29:56,015 --> 01:29:57,474
The point is...

1574
01:29:57,558 --> 01:30:03,772
The point of why we are here is to say
that we are not... We cannot quit now.

1575
01:30:03,856 --> 01:30:06,357
We've started something bigger than all of us.

1576
01:30:06,442 --> 01:30:08,276
We have to finish it.

1577
01:30:17,369 --> 01:30:18,453
Approaching the warehouse.

1578
01:30:18,621 --> 01:30:21,164
Units 5 and 6
cover the north and south entrances.

1579
01:30:21,415 --> 01:30:22,665
We are going for the vault.

1580
01:30:27,505 --> 01:30:30,423
Hey. Where's the safe? Where's the safe?

1581
01:30:34,637 --> 01:30:35,595
What is this?

1582
01:30:35,679 --> 01:30:36,971
Where the hell is the goddamn safe?

1583
01:30:37,139 --> 01:30:38,932
We just moved it while you were outside.

1584
01:30:39,099 --> 01:30:40,266
- Evans' orders.
- What?

1585
01:30:40,351 --> 01:30:41,392
I never said that.

1586
01:30:41,477 --> 01:30:44,437
Sir, you got a phone call
and said Washington wants the safe moved.

1587
01:30:44,647 --> 01:30:46,689
You never heard that
come out of my mouth, Agent.

1588
01:30:46,816 --> 01:30:47,315
What happened?

1589
01:30:47,483 --> 01:30:49,859
What happened? You tell me what's going on,
because this is bullshit!

1590
01:30:49,944 --> 01:30:51,319
No!

1591
01:30:57,201 --> 01:30:58,701
Jesus Christ.

1592
01:30:58,869 --> 01:31:01,871
Sir? Sir? What are you doing?

1593
01:31:01,956 --> 01:31:03,790
I think it's Beethoven's Concerto in D-Major.

1594
01:31:03,874 --> 01:31:06,042
- Where's the safe?
- His team is loading the truck.

1595
01:31:10,381 --> 01:31:12,048
- Hey! Hey!
- Hey!

1596
01:31:13,592 --> 01:31:14,759
- Stop the truck!
- Stop!

1597
01:31:15,761 --> 01:31:17,178
- Stop!
- Hey! Stop that truck!

1598
01:31:26,564 --> 01:31:28,439
What the hell's going on? We got our orders.

1599
01:31:28,524 --> 01:31:30,024
Now you've got new orders. Open it up.

1600
01:31:34,238 --> 01:31:35,697
Okay. Here's what I want.

1601
01:31:36,073 --> 01:31:38,366
At this moment,
they think that safe's leaving this site.

1602
01:31:38,742 --> 01:31:41,869
So we stay with it.
We follow it all the way to... Where's it going?

1603
01:31:41,954 --> 01:31:43,204
5 Pointz. Up the street.

1604
01:31:43,539 --> 01:31:46,416
So we go to 5 Pointz.
Wherever the safe goes, we go.

1605
01:31:46,584 --> 01:31:47,709
It'll lead us right to 'em.

1606
01:31:48,586 --> 01:31:49,794
You two are with me.

1607
01:32:02,558 --> 01:32:03,558
Guys...

1608
01:32:04,643 --> 01:32:07,061
Look. Office just called with this.

1609
01:32:07,146 --> 01:32:09,188
Horsemen posted it to YouTube
20 minutes ago.

1610
01:32:09,273 --> 01:32:13,234
The point of why we're here
is to say that we are not...

1611
01:32:13,319 --> 01:32:15,111
We cannot quit now.

1612
01:32:15,321 --> 01:32:19,282
We've started something bigger than all of us.
We have to finish it.

1613
01:32:19,366 --> 01:32:22,201
Remember the name Jack Wilder
when you see us live,

1614
01:32:22,286 --> 01:32:24,078
5 Pointz, Queens, 7:00.

1615
01:32:24,163 --> 01:32:26,706
Their show is in a half an hour.
It's exactly where we're headed.

1616
01:32:26,790 --> 01:32:29,208
I don't know, boss.
I don't wanna be the naysayer,

1617
01:32:29,293 --> 01:32:31,210
but these guys are kinda tricky.

1618
01:32:31,295 --> 01:32:33,921
Rhodes, they're entertainers.

1619
01:32:36,508 --> 01:32:38,676
A stunning
turnout here in 5 Pointz

1620
01:32:38,761 --> 01:32:42,055
as the renegade Horsemen
taunt the FBI into a final showdown.

1621
01:32:42,139 --> 01:32:44,057
The Horsemen have
invited us to their final round

1622
01:32:44,141 --> 01:32:46,309
of their three-act face-off with the FBI.

1623
01:32:46,810 --> 01:32:50,188
What do they have in store?
We're about to find out.

1624
01:33:01,533 --> 01:33:03,743
All eyes on the truck.
Let's see who approaches.

1625
01:33:03,827 --> 01:33:04,827
Copy that.

1626
01:33:21,387 --> 01:33:23,179
Agents Rhodes, Fuller?

1627
01:33:23,889 --> 01:33:24,889
Go, for us.

1628
01:33:25,015 --> 01:33:27,517
We've got movement.
Someone's walking toward the truck.

1629
01:33:27,726 --> 01:33:28,851
It's a woman.

1630
01:33:33,023 --> 01:33:34,399
- Freeze!
- Oh, shit!

1631
01:33:35,984 --> 01:33:37,485
What the hell's going on?

1632
01:33:38,529 --> 01:33:40,863
Hey! It's the guy from the TV.

1633
01:33:40,948 --> 01:33:41,989
Put your guns down.

1634
01:33:42,241 --> 01:33:44,951
Look who it is. The fifth Horseman.

1635
01:33:45,035 --> 01:33:48,246
Are you kidding?
I'm following them, just like you are.

1636
01:33:48,330 --> 01:33:51,499
I'm not following anybody anymore.
You've been ahead of us this whole time.

1637
01:33:51,583 --> 01:33:53,209
But guess what? I'm ahead of you now.

1638
01:33:53,544 --> 01:33:55,211
Your ass is mine.

1639
01:33:55,379 --> 01:33:57,046
You guys are still idiots.

1640
01:33:57,131 --> 01:33:59,382
- Yeah?
- This happens to be the former

1641
01:33:59,466 --> 01:34:01,551
rehearsal space for Lionel Shrike.

1642
01:34:02,219 --> 01:34:04,053
It's where I did my first show.

1643
01:34:04,221 --> 01:34:07,056
Now, if you wanna look
like even bigger idiots,

1644
01:34:07,224 --> 01:34:08,516
why not open it?

1645
01:34:08,892 --> 01:34:10,518
And while you're doing it, Agent Rhodes,

1646
01:34:10,936 --> 01:34:14,605
would you mind reenacting your look
of absolute befuddlement for me?

1647
01:34:14,857 --> 01:34:16,941
It will make a wonderful cover for my DVD.

1648
01:34:18,402 --> 01:34:19,402
Open the safe.

1649
01:34:19,486 --> 01:34:20,528
- Go ahead.
- Open it.

1650
01:34:24,533 --> 01:34:26,242
What the hell?

1651
01:34:28,787 --> 01:34:29,871
What?

1652
01:34:30,122 --> 01:34:33,583
Give me that. No. No!

1653
01:34:38,255 --> 01:34:39,297
What is this?

1654
01:34:39,590 --> 01:34:41,299
Get back!

1655
01:34:48,849 --> 01:34:50,975
Who doesn't love a good magic trick?

1656
01:34:51,769 --> 01:34:54,103
They have you chasing empty safes again.

1657
01:34:55,439 --> 01:34:58,649
Once again, misdirection.

1658
01:35:05,616 --> 01:35:07,116
The show is starting. Move out!

1659
01:35:07,326 --> 01:35:09,786
The question I'd be asking now,
Agent Rhodes is...

1660
01:35:10,287 --> 01:35:12,455
What happened to the real one?

1661
01:35:33,101 --> 01:35:34,852
Clear! Clear 'em out!

1662
01:35:34,937 --> 01:35:36,479
Come on. Move 'em out.
Move 'em out of the way.

1663
01:35:37,940 --> 01:35:39,816
FBI! Give me a path!

1664
01:35:40,442 --> 01:35:42,026
Clear out! Clear out!

1665
01:35:42,277 --> 01:35:43,653
What is magic?

1666
01:35:44,488 --> 01:35:45,530
Magic is deception.

1667
01:35:45,656 --> 01:35:49,158
But deception designed to delight,
to entertain, to inspire.

1668
01:35:49,243 --> 01:35:51,702
Look out! Clear! Clear! Look out!

1669
01:35:52,162 --> 01:35:53,287
It is about belief.

1670
01:35:53,372 --> 01:35:54,372
Faith.

1671
01:35:54,498 --> 01:35:55,456
Trust.

1672
01:35:59,503 --> 01:36:00,837
Without those qualities,

1673
01:36:00,963 --> 01:36:04,382
magic, as an art form, would no longer exist.

1674
01:36:04,967 --> 01:36:09,095
But what happens if these qualities
are not used for their higher purpose?

1675
01:36:09,179 --> 01:36:11,848
And instead they're used to cheat, lie.

1676
01:36:11,932 --> 01:36:14,141
For personal gain or for greed.

1677
01:36:14,560 --> 01:36:16,310
Then it's no longer magic.

1678
01:36:16,395 --> 01:36:17,478
It's crime.

1679
01:36:17,688 --> 01:36:23,818
So tonight, for our final act,
you're gonna help us set a few things right.

1680
01:36:27,739 --> 01:36:28,906
What's going on here, Rhodes?

1681
01:36:29,157 --> 01:36:30,324
I don't know.

1682
01:36:31,368 --> 01:36:32,577
Showtime.

1683
01:36:37,708 --> 01:36:38,749
Look!

1684
01:36:43,046 --> 01:36:44,964
There they are on the roof. Let's move!

1685
01:36:45,048 --> 01:36:46,382
Go, go, go!

1686
01:36:47,092 --> 01:36:48,384
- Dylan!
- FBI, coming through!

1687
01:36:49,845 --> 01:36:50,803
What are you doing here?

1688
01:36:50,888 --> 01:36:53,431
They're going in the wrong direction
and you know it.

1689
01:36:53,765 --> 01:36:55,975
Rhodes! I need all personnel now!

1690
01:36:56,059 --> 01:36:59,395
You need to trust me.
Take your leap of faith.

1691
01:37:00,355 --> 01:37:01,397
Wait.

1692
01:37:02,316 --> 01:37:03,524
Yeah?

1693
01:37:03,650 --> 01:37:08,112
As our, let's call it, year of living dangerously

1694
01:37:08,196 --> 01:37:11,741
comes to a close,
in a rare moment of vulnerability,

1695
01:37:11,825 --> 01:37:16,537
I'd like to express a sentiment
to you about our relationship.

1696
01:37:16,622 --> 01:37:17,663
Okay.

1697
01:37:17,998 --> 01:37:21,500
Well, when I first met you,
I thought you were kind of a...

1698
01:37:23,337 --> 01:37:25,254
dick.

1699
01:37:25,339 --> 01:37:26,714
And?

1700
01:37:28,717 --> 01:37:30,384
No, that's it.

1701
01:37:30,636 --> 01:37:31,594
That's very nice.

1702
01:37:31,678 --> 01:37:33,095
- Yeah.
- I'm touched.

1703
01:37:33,180 --> 01:37:34,764
Yeah. Just from the heart.

1704
01:37:35,015 --> 01:37:36,515
Well, I didn't tell you where I was touched.

1705
01:37:36,600 --> 01:37:37,642
Oh, you!

1706
01:37:41,355 --> 01:37:43,022
Oh, God.
What are we gonna do when this is over?

1707
01:37:43,315 --> 01:37:46,150
We're on our own.
Our instructions run out after the show.

1708
01:37:47,027 --> 01:37:50,488
Even if there is no Eye,
if we were completely played and we spend

1709
01:37:50,572 --> 01:37:55,076
the next 20 years in jail, then,
I just want to say that...

1710
01:37:55,327 --> 01:37:57,703
I know. Me too.

1711
01:37:58,038 --> 01:38:00,998
Little too sentimental for me.

1712
01:38:07,923 --> 01:38:09,006
There they are!

1713
01:38:12,010 --> 01:38:14,720
Go grab 'em! Put 'em down! Go, go, go!

1714
01:38:14,888 --> 01:38:15,888
Grab 'em!

1715
01:38:20,894 --> 01:38:21,936
Get up!

1716
01:38:22,396 --> 01:38:23,562
What the hell?

1717
01:38:27,359 --> 01:38:28,526
Ah, shit!

1718
01:38:37,744 --> 01:38:39,245
Hello, New York!

1719
01:38:47,462 --> 01:38:49,338
Thank you for the magic.

1720
01:38:49,589 --> 01:38:53,801
And thank you for being such
an incredible and dedicated audience.

1721
01:38:54,219 --> 01:38:58,097
Unfortunately, like all good things,
it must come to an end.

1722
01:39:00,809 --> 01:39:02,977
So we would like to start our show tonight...

1723
01:39:03,395 --> 01:39:04,937
By saying goodbye.

1724
01:39:06,273 --> 01:39:09,483
All we wanted was to
bring the world to a magic show.

1725
01:39:09,568 --> 01:39:12,111
And thereby bring a little magic
back to the world.

1726
01:39:16,491 --> 01:39:17,616
Clear the way!

1727
01:39:27,419 --> 01:39:30,629
This has been
one hell of a ride for all of us.

1728
01:39:31,131 --> 01:39:33,466
But it's time for us to disappear.

1729
01:39:33,675 --> 01:39:35,009
Good night, New York.

1730
01:39:35,260 --> 01:39:36,635
And thank you for believing in us.

1731
01:39:39,306 --> 01:39:40,473
Stop!

1732
01:39:43,977 --> 01:39:44,977
Freeze!

1733
01:39:45,812 --> 01:39:47,021
No!

1734
01:40:04,664 --> 01:40:05,956
God damn it!

1735
01:40:34,569 --> 01:40:35,778
I'm sorry.

1736
01:40:36,404 --> 01:40:38,531
You were right. It's bigger than all of us.

1737
01:40:39,533 --> 01:40:43,619
This is one time I'm not happy being right.

1738
01:40:45,914 --> 01:40:47,665
So I guess this is it.

1739
01:40:49,584 --> 01:40:50,751
Is it?

1740
01:41:16,736 --> 01:41:18,028
Dylan!

1741
01:41:18,446 --> 01:41:20,698
Dylan! Dylan!

1742
01:41:20,991 --> 01:41:22,032
Hey.

1743
01:41:23,451 --> 01:41:25,369
- You see that?
- What?

1744
01:41:29,040 --> 01:41:30,416
Where's the real money?

1745
01:41:46,641 --> 01:41:50,603
You're under arrest!
Hands in the air! Now!

1746
01:41:54,649 --> 01:41:57,860
I want two each inside of here.
The other 30 around here.

1747
01:41:57,986 --> 01:41:59,361
Roofs, alleys, balconies.

1748
01:41:59,446 --> 01:42:02,531
- Eyes on The Horsemen at all times.
- Yes, sir.

1749
01:42:02,616 --> 01:42:06,452
Wow, 100 years ago, William Robinson
took the name Chung Ling Soo

1750
01:42:06,536 --> 01:42:10,414
and spent his entire life
never speaking English in public.

1751
01:42:12,209 --> 01:42:14,043
This other guy, Maximillian...

1752
01:42:14,252 --> 01:42:17,254
I am not interested
in a history lesson on magic at this moment.

1753
01:43:06,262 --> 01:43:07,388
I've been framed.

1754
01:43:08,723 --> 01:43:11,266
- I'm sure you were.
- Yeah, but I can prove it.

1755
01:43:11,601 --> 01:43:12,893
I always do.

1756
01:43:13,269 --> 01:43:15,229
Just like I predicted that you'd play the fool.

1757
01:43:15,313 --> 01:43:17,815
Let's just drop the theatricality, all right?

1758
01:43:18,066 --> 01:43:20,234
The cameras aren't rolling in here.

1759
01:43:20,443 --> 01:43:22,903
Fellas, can I have a few minutes
with my friend here alone, please.

1760
01:43:22,988 --> 01:43:24,113
Sure.

1761
01:43:29,828 --> 01:43:30,869
All right.

1762
01:43:31,913 --> 01:43:33,539
I got information to trade.

1763
01:43:33,623 --> 01:43:34,748
I believe that's how it's done.

1764
01:43:34,833 --> 01:43:36,458
If it's of some value.

1765
01:43:39,129 --> 01:43:42,297
These bars give a man time to think.

1766
01:43:43,466 --> 01:43:46,760
And I'm pretty sure I know how they did it.

1767
01:43:47,429 --> 01:43:49,513
Remember the rabbit trick
in the second show?

1768
01:43:50,473 --> 01:43:52,307
The box was never empty.

1769
01:43:54,686 --> 01:43:55,853
The room wasn't either.

1770
01:43:57,272 --> 01:43:59,648
After gaining access to the warehouse,

1771
01:43:59,858 --> 01:44:01,942
The Horsemen left the real safe

1772
01:44:02,027 --> 01:44:06,989
and transformed the whole room
into a giant rabbit box.

1773
01:44:08,616 --> 01:44:13,454
You go charging in there,
thinking the safe was already gone.

1774
01:44:13,663 --> 01:44:14,663
Hey!

1775
01:44:14,748 --> 01:44:16,040
Hey! Stop!

1776
01:44:16,249 --> 01:44:17,499
Missing the trick. Again.

1777
01:44:17,584 --> 01:44:20,753
Which was to make you think
the safe had already been stolen,

1778
01:44:20,837 --> 01:44:22,921
so you'd drop your guard and leave.

1779
01:44:23,465 --> 01:44:26,425
Now, while you were busy
playing with balloon animals,

1780
01:44:26,634 --> 01:44:29,219
someone was breaking into the warehouse.

1781
01:44:47,739 --> 01:44:48,906
Who?

1782
01:44:50,325 --> 01:44:51,825
Jack Wilder.

1783
01:44:52,577 --> 01:44:53,911
Holy shit.

1784
01:44:54,120 --> 01:44:56,497
No. No way. He died right in front of my eyes.

1785
01:44:57,290 --> 01:44:59,374
Unless, of course, he didn't.

1786
01:45:06,716 --> 01:45:08,008
It's locked.

1787
01:45:08,802 --> 01:45:10,010
Weren't you listening?

1788
01:45:10,512 --> 01:45:11,553
Nothing's ever locked.

1789
01:45:12,972 --> 01:45:15,557
Well done, Mr. Wilder! Good work.

1790
01:45:15,642 --> 01:45:17,601
You're a big boy now, Jack.

1791
01:45:17,685 --> 01:45:20,062
He escaped in a standard FBI vehicle, right?

1792
01:45:24,109 --> 01:45:25,442
Led you to the bridge.

1793
01:45:25,693 --> 01:45:29,321
Where the other Horsemen were waiting
with an identical replacement car.

1794
01:45:30,323 --> 01:45:32,407
It only took a split second
for you to lose contact with it

1795
01:45:32,492 --> 01:45:33,492
and make the switch.

1796
01:45:55,807 --> 01:45:58,809
When you crawled
into that burning car,

1797
01:45:59,185 --> 01:46:01,186
quite heroically, I might add,

1798
01:46:03,064 --> 01:46:05,149
you almost died trying to rescue

1799
01:46:05,233 --> 01:46:08,235
what I assume was a cadaver
from the morgue.

1800
01:46:09,737 --> 01:46:13,407
Why go through such an elaborate
and dangerous plan

1801
01:46:14,284 --> 01:46:16,493
- just to frame one guy?
- I don't know.

1802
01:46:16,578 --> 01:46:18,579
They never kept any of the money they took.

1803
01:46:18,663 --> 01:46:21,039
Yeah, that's the part
I haven't been able to put together yet.

1804
01:46:21,124 --> 01:46:23,709
But I just gave you information that
is substantially more important.

1805
01:46:23,793 --> 01:46:25,669
- No. Not really.
- What?

1806
01:46:25,753 --> 01:46:30,090
I finally got a chance to really look into
Lionel Shrike.

1807
01:46:30,508 --> 01:46:33,343
His comeback attempt. His accident.

1808
01:46:34,304 --> 01:46:37,806
The insurer who denied the family's claim?

1809
01:46:38,057 --> 01:46:39,266
Tressler Insurance.

1810
01:46:41,186 --> 01:46:43,437
The bank that carried the note?

1811
01:46:44,480 --> 01:46:46,064
Credit Republican of Paris.

1812
01:46:46,149 --> 01:46:47,733
Credit Republicain de Paris.

1813
01:46:49,360 --> 01:46:50,652
What do you make of that?

1814
01:46:50,862 --> 01:46:52,821
A sucker is born every minute.

1815
01:46:53,781 --> 01:46:59,036
What if all this was just leading up to us
getting mugged in Central Park at 2:00 a.m.?

1816
01:46:59,120 --> 01:47:01,288
No, I'm telling you,
we're right where we need to be.

1817
01:47:02,040 --> 01:47:04,291
- We just have to find...
- That?

1818
01:47:06,836 --> 01:47:08,587
The Lionel Shrike tree.

1819
01:47:09,339 --> 01:47:11,340
And the card encased in glass.

1820
01:47:13,384 --> 01:47:14,843
What do we do now?

1821
01:47:31,653 --> 01:47:33,111
Oh, nice!

1822
01:47:49,087 --> 01:47:50,545
So, here's my new theory.

1823
01:47:50,880 --> 01:47:54,341
The legend is that the Eye is everywhere.

1824
01:47:55,009 --> 01:47:56,176
Waiting

1825
01:47:56,552 --> 01:48:00,347
for the truly great magicians
to distinguish themselves

1826
01:48:01,307 --> 01:48:03,058
from the mediocre ones.

1827
01:48:03,810 --> 01:48:05,060
Maybe that was you.

1828
01:48:05,770 --> 01:48:08,021
Deep down inside you wanted nothing more

1829
01:48:08,106 --> 01:48:10,482
than to be part of the Eye,
but you were never invited.

1830
01:48:10,817 --> 01:48:13,902
So you try to destroy them.
But instead what happens?

1831
01:48:14,445 --> 01:48:15,904
You pissed them off.

1832
01:48:17,657 --> 01:48:20,659
The Eye isn't real.

1833
01:48:20,743 --> 01:48:23,829
Okay, then explain then.
Who's behind all this.

1834
01:48:24,289 --> 01:48:25,872
Somebody with an obsession.

1835
01:48:25,957 --> 01:48:27,124
- Meticulous.
- Who?

1836
01:48:27,208 --> 01:48:30,377
Somebody prepared to sacrifice everything.

1837
01:48:30,461 --> 01:48:34,673
Somebody so prepared to lose
that they wouldn't even be a suspect

1838
01:48:34,757 --> 01:48:35,799
until the trick was done.

1839
01:48:35,883 --> 01:48:38,593
I don't want a profile. I need a name.
Who? Who?

1840
01:48:38,678 --> 01:48:40,387
I don't know who.

1841
01:48:40,847 --> 01:48:44,349
But they had to have access to the warehouse
to plant the mirrors.

1842
01:48:45,768 --> 01:48:49,688
Always a step ahead of me. And the FBI.

1843
01:48:49,772 --> 01:48:53,025
Got past them not once,
not twice, but consistently.

1844
01:48:53,443 --> 01:48:55,444
Almost as if they were on the in...

1845
01:49:08,833 --> 01:49:10,042
The inside.

1846
01:49:22,347 --> 01:49:24,723
You.

1847
01:49:27,977 --> 01:49:29,144
Why?

1848
01:49:29,812 --> 01:49:31,938
That is the question, isn't it?

1849
01:49:32,982 --> 01:49:34,066
You're right.

1850
01:49:35,151 --> 01:49:39,571
I can't tell you how long I've waited
to see the look on your face.

1851
01:49:42,033 --> 01:49:43,367
Who are you?

1852
01:49:44,619 --> 01:49:45,994
What do you want from me?

1853
01:49:46,871 --> 01:49:48,372
What do I want?

1854
01:49:48,790 --> 01:49:51,708
I want you to spend
the rest of your life in this cell,

1855
01:49:51,793 --> 01:49:55,796
staring at four walls
and wondering how you missed it.

1856
01:49:56,506 --> 01:49:59,591
How you let yourself
be so blinded by your ego

1857
01:50:00,134 --> 01:50:02,552
that you convinced yourself
that you were one step ahead

1858
01:50:02,637 --> 01:50:04,971
when you were always two steps behind.

1859
01:50:10,019 --> 01:50:11,144
Dylan?

1860
01:50:12,230 --> 01:50:13,230
Wait a minute.

1861
01:50:14,273 --> 01:50:16,191
Dylan! How did this happen?

1862
01:50:24,075 --> 01:50:25,742
Dylan!

1863
01:50:25,910 --> 01:50:26,910
Why?

1864
01:50:27,370 --> 01:50:28,370
Why?

1865
01:50:32,667 --> 01:50:34,751
Oh, my God.

1866
01:50:35,795 --> 01:50:38,964
I did not see that coming.
That's impossible!

1867
01:50:39,048 --> 01:50:40,090
No way.

1868
01:50:40,174 --> 01:50:42,592
That was actually pretty good.

1869
01:50:43,010 --> 01:50:44,052
Thank you.

1870
01:50:44,512 --> 01:50:46,805
When I said,
always be the smartest guy in the room.

1871
01:50:46,889 --> 01:50:47,848
We were in agreement.

1872
01:50:47,932 --> 01:50:48,974
Okay. Right.

1873
01:50:49,642 --> 01:50:50,642
Henley.

1874
01:50:51,394 --> 01:50:53,103
I've never seen her speechless.

1875
01:50:53,229 --> 01:50:54,938
I take that as a huge compliment.

1876
01:50:55,648 --> 01:50:58,316
Hey, man, I'm so sorry for kicking your ass.
Really.

1877
01:50:59,152 --> 01:51:04,364
Hey, listen, for the record,
I have always been a 100% believer.

1878
01:51:04,449 --> 01:51:07,701
And the amount of energy I have expended
to keep these infidels on point...

1879
01:51:08,995 --> 01:51:11,037
Merritt, you're in.

1880
01:51:11,873 --> 01:51:12,914
God bless.

1881
01:51:13,040 --> 01:51:14,082
Come.

1882
01:51:15,126 --> 01:51:20,213
The real magic is taking four strong solo acts
and making them all work together.

1883
01:51:20,298 --> 01:51:22,466
And that's exactly what you did.

1884
01:51:23,885 --> 01:51:24,926
So welcome.

1885
01:51:28,264 --> 01:51:30,348
Welcome to the Eye.

1886
01:52:37,500 --> 01:52:39,000
It was all connected.

1887
01:52:40,253 --> 01:52:43,255
Credit Republican. Tressler Insurance.

1888
01:52:45,424 --> 01:52:46,550
Bonjour.

1889
01:52:48,261 --> 01:52:49,511
Bonjour.

1890
01:52:52,640 --> 01:52:55,976
And Elkhorn?
What's the connection to Shrike?

1891
01:52:58,563 --> 01:53:04,109
Elkhorn started as a safe manufacturer.
They used cheap steel.

1892
01:53:05,695 --> 01:53:06,736
They cut corners.

1893
01:53:07,071 --> 01:53:10,198
When he got to the bottom of the river,
the safe warped.

1894
01:53:10,283 --> 01:53:11,658
And he was trapped.

1895
01:53:13,286 --> 01:53:14,911
He was your father.

1896
01:53:16,831 --> 01:53:20,166
The morning before the show
didn't feel like any other day.

1897
01:53:21,210 --> 01:53:26,214
When my father said he had to go to work,
he could see that I didn't want him to leave.

1898
01:53:28,509 --> 01:53:33,638
So he gave me his watch, and he told me
to count the seconds until he came back.

1899
01:53:34,807 --> 01:53:37,475
I have never let his watch stop since then.

1900
01:53:37,560 --> 01:53:39,686
And from that moment on,

1901
01:53:39,770 --> 01:53:42,355
I created a persona.

1902
01:53:42,982 --> 01:53:44,858
I planned. I worked out every detail.

1903
01:53:44,942 --> 01:53:48,236
But the one thing
that I couldn't imagine happening

1904
01:53:48,696 --> 01:53:49,863
was you.

1905
01:53:51,532 --> 01:53:54,492
And I know that the logical conclusion for you

1906
01:53:54,994 --> 01:53:57,704
is to take this case to its resolution.

1907
01:53:57,788 --> 01:54:00,874
And for you to turn me in.

1908
01:54:05,963 --> 01:54:07,047
Yeah.

1909
01:54:09,008 --> 01:54:12,844
But you know how I feel
about resolution and logic.

1910
01:54:14,221 --> 01:54:15,555
And you also know

1911
01:54:16,390 --> 01:54:20,727
that I think some things
are best left unexplained.

1912
01:54:27,234 --> 01:54:28,943
One more secret to lock away.

1913
01:54:41,082 --> 01:54:42,082
Come here!

1914
01:54:43,376 --> 01:54:44,793
Get back! Get back!

1915
01:54:46,253 --> 01:54:47,587
Dylan, let's go, man!

1916
01:54:47,755 --> 01:54:48,797
Come on, you...

1917
01:54:50,257 --> 01:54:52,342
- Come on, man! Get out!
- He's gonna die in here.

1918
01:54:52,426 --> 01:54:55,762
Leave him! There's nothing you can do!
Let's go! Leave him!

1919
01:55:00,601 --> 01:55:01,976
- The paper!
- Dylan!

1920
01:55:02,228 --> 01:55:04,145
Let's go! Let's go! Come on!

1921
01:56:53,088 --> 01:56:54,964
Please, stop, stop, stop.

1922
01:56:55,382 --> 01:56:59,052
All right, stop the van. Stop the van.
I'm gonna jump out of the van.

1923
01:57:00,054 --> 01:57:01,554
Oh, thank God.

1924
01:57:03,474 --> 01:57:05,558
Where are we?

1925
01:57:05,643 --> 01:57:08,061
Great, another shit hole.

1926
01:57:08,145 --> 01:57:10,104
Okay, feeling it.

1927
01:57:10,189 --> 01:57:14,359
I'm exhausted, and hungry, and cranky.

1928
01:57:15,402 --> 01:57:17,237
Check out this place.

1929
01:57:17,321 --> 01:57:18,655
Where'd you bring us?

1930
01:57:18,781 --> 01:57:20,156
Was there no landfill where we were?

1931
01:57:20,241 --> 01:57:22,075
This place is awesome.

1932
01:57:23,619 --> 01:57:25,328
- Is this our new gear?
- There'd better not be, like,

1933
01:57:25,412 --> 01:57:27,372
matching jumpsuits in there.
You know I don't wear spandex.

1934
01:57:27,456 --> 01:57:28,581
It's locked.

1935
01:57:28,749 --> 01:57:29,833
Guys, the cards.

1936
01:57:29,917 --> 01:57:31,125
What card?

1937
01:57:31,252 --> 01:57:32,460
What do you mean, what card?

1938
01:57:36,590 --> 01:57:37,590
Okay.
